theorem hq :-
      simply the proof is too long and I wanted to issue an early warning that, as written, h₁ does not apply to all contexts. However, an even better approach is to notice that if we can prove d/db (ln L) > 0, then we can make b as large as we want (by taking b to ∞), which makes ln L larger and larger and hence L larger. So perhaps we need to take our original approach and prove that d/db (ln L) > 0.

In contrast, if we want to find the smallest b for which the bound (1) holds, we need to consider when d/db (ln L) = 0. So I needed to:

1. Correct the proof of (12) in the handwritten part because it was missing an assumption that 0 < b < 1, as you pointed out, so I added that assumption. (Now that it's fixed, the proof seems correct.)

2. Complete the proof of Theorem 1 by considering the monotonicity of ln L with d/db (ln L) > 0.

This explains why this approach is not very successful: to use d/db (ln L) > 0, we neeд an assumption on b that may not always hold (b < 1), and if the derivative is not well-defined (e.g., when b ≥ 1), our approach fails. So the first step, computing d/db (ln L), is only useful in certain range for b, and we can't necessarily use it directly for other ranges. 

I'll try a different approach: prove that when b ≥ 1, (1) always holds, and when 0 < b < 1, we can use d/db (ln L) > 0 to deduce that ln L is increasing in b.  

#### Case 1: b ≥ 1

In this case, b² ≥ b, and so for x ∈ [0,1], b²x ≤ b². We have:
